Dataset Description¶

The dataset used for this project has been obtained from https://www.kaggle.com/mlg-ulb/creditcardfraud The data contains transaction details from European Card Holders such most of the features have been reduced by Principal Component Analysis due to privacy issues. The features from V1 to V28 were obtained by PCA meaning that they were scalled before applying PCA. The only features that were not transformed by PCA are Time and Amount. Time indicated the seconds that ellapsed between the transactions, amount gives the value transacted during the transaction. The feature of interest is the Class, that is a binary variable with 1 in case a transaction is fraud and 0 if its legitimate.

Its clear that the classes are highly imbalanced and almost all the transactions are not fraudulent. With this class imbalance, the machine learning models might overffit because they might "think" that most of the transactions are actually not fraud and thus this might lead to some errors.

Class imbalance is a quite common problem when working with real-world data—samples from one class or multiple classes are over-represented in a dataset. Intuitively, we can think of several domains where this may occur, such as spam filtering, fraud detection, or screening for diseases.

Because machine learning algorithms often optimize a reward or cost function derived as a total of the training instances seen during fitting, the decision rule is likely to be biased towards the majority class. In other words, the method implicitly develops a model that optimizes predictions based on the most abundant class in the dataset during training in order to reduce cost or maximize reward.

Outlier Detection¶

In [31]:
Q3 = np.percentile(df['Amount'], 75)
Q1 = np.percentile(df['Amount'], 25)

# set the cut
cutoff = 5.0

#the interquartile range
IQR = (Q3 - Q1)

# computing lower bound and upper bound
lower_bound = Q1 - (IQR * cutoff)
upper_bound = Q3 + (IQR * cutoff)

#  filter to remove values less than lower bound and greater than
# upper bound
filter_data = (df['Amount'] < lower_bound) | (df['Amount'] > upper_bound)

# filtering data
outliers = df[filter_data]['Amount']
fraud_outliers = df[(df['Class'] == 1) & filter_data]['Amount']
normal_outliers = df[(df['Class'] == 0) & filter_data]['Amount']

print(f"Total Number of Outliers : {outliers.count()}")
print(f"Number of Outliers in Fraudulent Class : {fraud_outliers.count()}")
print(f"No of Outliers in Normal Class : {normal_outliers.count()}")
print(f"Percentage of Fraud amount outliers : {round((fraud_outliers.count()/outliers.count())*100,2)}%")

Scaling the Datasets¶

In [34]:

The sub-sample of the data will be made to have a fifty-fifty percent ratio of the fraud and non-fraud cases. The sub-sample will be a new dataframe with the same number of frauds and non-fraud cases. This would help with the problem of wrong correlation and overfitting of the machine learning models

Up sampling the minority class, down sampling the majority class, and the fabrication of synthetic training samples are some strategies for dealing with class imbalance. Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique is the most commonly utilized algorithm for synthetic training sample generation (SMOTE).

There are 492 cases of fraud so I am going to get 492 cases of non-fraud so that a new datafreme is created. I then concat the 492 cases of fraud and non fraud, creating a new sub-sample.

The only columns left for scaling are time and amount

The sub-sample will be a data frame that has an equal ratio or same amount of the fraud and non-fraud cases. The major reason as to why a sub-sample is created is to deal with the class imbalances. This avoids overfitting problems and wrong correlations. With the look at the V features, we are not yet aware of the effect of these features on the target feauture.

There are 492 cases of the fraud cases in the dataset, therefore 492 cases of non-fraud can be created into the new sub dataframe. The 492 cases of fraud and non-fraud are then combined to create a new sub-sample.

Splitting the initial dataset for testing¶

Before performing the Random Under sampling technique, the original data frame which is the object df, is to be split. This is done for testing purposes. The models have to be tested on the original datasets but not on the datasets created from sampling techniques. The aim is to fit the model using the dataframes that have been undersampled or oversamples so that the model can detect patterns, and then test the models on the original datasets.

Since the data is imbalanced, the Stratified K-Fold split will be used.

Random under sampling technique¶

Random undersampling is done on the majority class in a data frame so that it matches the distribution of the minority classes that are to be predicted. Otherwise, training or making a model learn from the imbalanced data would result to overfitting or poor correlations amongst the independent and dependent variable.

The first step is to establish the imbalanced in the classes by couting the values. After that the non-fraud cases are brought to the same amount as the target fraud cases. This will give an equal amount of fraud and non-fraud cases. The next step is to then shuffle the data so that the models will maintain the same accuracy everytime

In [39]:

normal_distributed_df = pd.concat([fraud, non_fraud])

# And then Shuffle dataframe rows
new_df = normal_distributed_df.sample(frac=1, random_state=42)

Anomaly Detection from the Random sample's feature's¶

This procedure aims at removing the extreme outliers that have a high correlation with the target class, this step has a large impact on the performance of the models. The interquatile range method is being used here.

The interquartile range (IQR) calculates the difference between the 75th percentile and the 25th percentile, so a threshold is created beyond the 75th and 25th percentile so that any value that goes beyond this threshold is considered an anomaly. Boxplot can also be used to see the extreme outliers.

Its important to note that the lower the threshold, the more outliers it will detect. The focus here is to remove the extreme outliers so that the models do not get a lower accuracy. Extreme amount of information loss also has to be reduced so that model does not underfit.

from sklearn.model_selection import ShuffleSplit
from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve

def plot_learning_curve(estimator1, estimator2, estimator3, estimator4, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None,n_jobs=1, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    f, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(20,14), sharey=True)
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
        
    # First Estimator
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(estimator1, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    ax1.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,color="#ff9124")
    ax1.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="#2492ff")
    
    ax1.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#ff9124",label="Training score")
    
    ax1.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#2492ff",label="Cross-validation score")
    ax1.set_title("Logistic Regression Learning Curve", fontsize=14)
    ax1.set_xlabel('Training size (m)')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Score')
    ax1.grid(True)
    ax1.legend(loc="best")
    
    # Second Estimator 
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(estimator2, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    
    ax2.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,color="#ff9124")
    
    ax2.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="#2492ff")
    ax2.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#ff9124",label="Training score")
    ax2.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#2492ff",label="Cross-validation score")
    ax2.set_title("Knears Neighbors Learning Curve", fontsize=14)
    ax2.set_xlabel('Training size (m)')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Score')
    ax2.grid(True)
    ax2.legend(loc="best")
    
    
    # Third Estimator
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(estimator3, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    ax3.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,color="#ff9124")
    
    ax3.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="#2492ff")
    ax3.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#ff9124",label="Training score")
    ax3.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#2492ff",
             label="Cross-validation score")
    ax3.set_title("Support Vector Classifier \n Learning Curve", fontsize=14)
    ax3.set_xlabel('Training size (m)')
    ax3.set_ylabel('Score')
    ax3.grid(True)
    ax3.legend(loc="best")
    
    # Fourth Estimator
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(estimator4, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    ax4.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,color="#ff9124")
    
    ax4.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="#2492ff")
    ax4.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#ff9124",label="Training score")
    ax4.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="#2492ff",label="Cross-validation score")
    ax4.set_title("Random Forest Classifier \n Learning Curve", fontsize=14)
    ax4.set_xlabel('Training size (m)')
    ax4.set_ylabel('Score')
    ax4.grid(True)
    ax4.legend(loc="best")
    return plt

    plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))
    plt.title('ROC Curve \n Top 4 Classifiers', fontsize=18)
    plt.plot(log_fpr, log_tpr, label='Logistic Regression Classifier Score: {:.4f}'.format(roc_auc_score(y_train, log_reg_pred)))

    plt.plot(tree_fpr, tree_tpr, label='Random Forest Classifier Score: {:.4f}'.format(roc_auc_score(y_train, forest_pred)))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.axis([-0.01, 1, 0, 1])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate', fontsize=16)
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate', fontsize=16)
    plt.annotate('Minimum ROC Score of 50% \n (This is the minimum score to get)', xy=(0.5, 0.5), xytext=(0.6, 0.3),
                arrowprops=dict(facecolor='#6E726D', shrink=0.05),)
    plt.legend()

Applying the SMOTE Technique >>> Over sampling¶

SMOTE means Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling TEchnique. It creates new synthetic points in order to have an equal balance in the classes. SMOTE provides another way of dealing with the class imbalances.

SMOTE takes more time to execute, althought, it is more accurate then the under-sampling technique used before.

Testing SMOTE with Logistic Regression¶

In [57]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, RandomizedSearchCV


print('Length of X (train): {} | Length of y (train): {}'.format(len(original_Xtrain), len(original_Ytrain)))
print('Length of X (test): {} | Length of y (test): {}'.format(len(original_Xtest), len(original_Ytest)))

# List to append the score and then find the average
accuracy_lst = []
precision_lst = []
recall_lst = []
f1_lst = []
auc_lst = []

# Classifier with optimal parameters

log_reg_sm = LogisticRegression()

rand_log_reg = RandomizedSearchCV(LogisticRegression(), log_reg_params, n_iter=4)


# Implementing SMOTE Technique 

log_reg_params = {"penalty": ['l1', 'l2'], 'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000]}
for train, test in sss.split(original_Xtrain, original_Ytrain):
    pipeline = imbalanced_make_pipeline(SMOTE(sampling_strategy='minority'), rand_log_reg) # SMOTE happens during Cross Validation not before..
    model = pipeline.fit(original_Xtrain[train], original_Ytrain[train])
    best_est = rand_log_reg.best_estimator_
    prediction = best_est.predict(original_Xtrain[test])
    
    accuracy_lst.append(pipeline.score(original_Xtrain[test], original_Ytrain[test]))
    precision_lst.append(precision_score(original_Ytrain[test], prediction))
    recall_lst.append(recall_score(original_Ytrain[test], prediction))
    f1_lst.append(f1_score(original_Ytrain[test], prediction))
    auc_lst.append(roc_auc_score(original_Ytrain[test], prediction))
    
print('---' * 45)
print('')
print("accuracy: {}".format(np.mean(accuracy_lst)))
print("precision: {}".format(np.mean(precision_lst)))
print("recall: {}".format(np.mean(recall_lst)))
print("f1: {}".format(np.mean(f1_lst)))
print('---' * 45)
